Battle of the Blades: MP3 Players Against Mobiles.
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
From this, it seems clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons why a person should buy a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s hard to get a high-end, expensive gramophone at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
However, such music products on LPs do not originate and there is no objective reason for this, from a qualitative point of view.
However, if your shelves are squeezed by vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably at least dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true with music on the go, that is, music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For someone, it can be unacceptable to spend $8,000 on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan might hardly bite the headphones for $20 off the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life
Some state-of-the-art music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobile phones don’t do by chance.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to its primary functions, telephony and texting, it can play music and video, both record, have a better, a worse camera and maybe even navigate.
And when you consider smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no refrigerator can grill, and no TV can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy chips.
A handful of mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, usually much less.
In this direction, the music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap phones, you should expect that they won’t be playing for more than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the worse ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a handful of card readers can cope with the miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones without any reduction.
You don’t need any special software for players except for iPods.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players will create a music library by themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the name of the album, the genre or, for example, the user’s rating.
Some devices only display the tree structure of directories similar to Explorer in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to operate, mobiles are more capable
When choosing a particular device, be particularly interested in the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, the comfort of control.
If your music is primarily a backdrop and if you listen to it every day just for a short time on the tram, you just need any phone that plays MP3.
This is something that almost any mobile phone can do.
You don’t have to monitor too much what music formats your mobile phone or player can.
MP3 will handle all and the vast majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and in addition to it, the vast majority of instruments can also handle music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online, for example.
All you need to do is visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) and purchase a song or album via the mobile internet.
This service in itself could already be a good argument for the purchase of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is poor and is usually limited to fast-tracked radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, this method of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) is expected to dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile phones with them.
Whenever you get the urge to listen to something, you record the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you are always wearing headphones or at least a wire-free.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every mobile phone, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones are usually under 3,000.
For three and four thousand kroner you already get a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of output to regular headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped phones even with a 3.5 mm headphone jack cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy to operate.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - the players will be able to really control everyone.
The minimum of features, the similarity of the controls to the previous standard cassette player or even the gramophone is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of an incorrectly turned on mobile internet and subsequently a huge account for data transmission.
What kind of device to touch
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have slots on memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the corresponding card, you will fit in to two thousand kroner.
Be careful, though.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, touch on Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you’re one of the more demanding listeners, you’d rather reach out to specialized mobile phones – walkmanets (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of the operator is thus closer to a separate MP3 player.
