The same service and in the same price category up to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>4,000, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), MP3 players will take you away from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classics to be discounted.
Maybe it won't be long.
About the fact that Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe, we have written many times on Mobil.cz.
This was confirmed by the Czech Republic, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are kept so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks here and penetration is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to bet that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, they are often invited by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who has stated several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It’s probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably doesn’t have too many chances anymore (by the way, it would probably be hard to look for the frequencies).
But there is another option – a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought about a significant reduction in prices, to which the classic operators had to respond.
Even before the launch of Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK as in the UK.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth-largest operator there.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they have far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite good to bet on a non-triggered target group.
This is because the operator focuses specifically on men.
“Administrative men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be captured by us.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look too hopeful.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokesman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, he is trying to do everything in his power to prevent any potential competitor from forming.
Interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a strong interest in being able to offer our customers not only solid, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in the negotiations with some of them," says Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
So maybe he's blinking for a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should expect the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its formation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not think that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no subject with a comprehensive and serious project in this area has contacted us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>en, from the press office of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2, said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also referring to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in a rare way to the O2 statement: "We have not yet recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business project on which it could be further built."
He adds: “It’s hard to find a virtual operator on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would already have to have a specific agreement on the table in order to be able to think about it in this short term."
Vodafone is reluctant to meet the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: “By negotiating with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when the operators are about something, they are able to pull a rope, also testifies to the formation of the U:phone.
Probably the greatest pressure towards the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the creation of the U:phone from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
Now, however, U:phone is suitable as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> added: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been reinforced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
However, in view of this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of Czech regulators is directly striking.
This is not just about the attitude of the Czech Republic, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic – unlike the UK and other developed countries – does not have the power to interfere in competition.
They belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (OECD).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
“A virtual operator’s entry into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the EEAS said in answer to our question.
From the representatives of the operators, the expression thus formulated is probably not surprising.
From an authority to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one exploits their position on the market, this is more than considered.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators operate normally, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile phone services."
However, it seems that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not in the interests of the OCTs.
In fact, shocking to the whole case is the tangible convergence of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if it is really just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
Just like the exact same price of gasoline at the pumping stations, it is certainly just a matter of chance and a tough competitive fight.
“The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have a corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to meet the telecom regulator,” Chalup said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not allow this argument, it should be at least a warning for the EEA that the three mobile operators are acting in a conspicuous manner.
However, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all operators.
The exercise of responsibility for the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS gives away from the whole matter.
We've met him in a couple of similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted novel of the telecommunications law, the extension of the competence of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the field of competition in telecommunications failed to promote, although a number of experts promised an improvement in the situation.
The UOHS representatives need to know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It works when no one is looking
However, the operation of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile phone services, which are public only in part.
This is usually the case for companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services such as Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts against the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there were cases you are talking about, it could be a breach of the terms of the contract that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company in question," said Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activity would not be tolerated by responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, none of the operators will stop this process.
In fact, these companies have immeasurable profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it in full as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that’s what should be at least strange.
In addition, another question is being raised for <0xC3><0x9A>ohs.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UCITS has relatively strong powers to disclose similar activities and, if it does not wish, does not have to be satisfied with the operator’s explanation that they have no knowledge of such activities and their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As it has fallen several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
Virtually in all countries where virtual operators were created, the classical operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small, possibly too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at this very moment that regulators intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created and another one was added to it.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are throwing the whole case over like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the ambiguity in competencies is more than suited to them in these cases.
But let's not put the flour in the grain.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will really soon appear with us, the Czech mobile market may be expanding again.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OHCHR to remain ineligible to refuse (discriminate) other interested parties.
And we must stop calling the rails than in the rest of Europe.
