Even rats have feelings.
When rats or squirrels run away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
The neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same when they behave in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge" for several years, contributions of well-known scientists have been published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove it so far, when we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all the human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we begin to engage in a different kind and open up the questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter unprepared territory because the hardware does not agree.
When a rat is in danger, it will do the same as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, run away, or attack.
People behave in a similar way, which some scientists consider to be a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe it, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share in short-term memory and performing or controlling functions).
This vast area is much more developed in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that a person is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden by the language essence of a person: because so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter to language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, no matter how constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is not even possible to measure or, because of special hardware, to analyze on the basis of our own experience, we are confronted with great problems by its exploration.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but in addition there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to investigate processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in the studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, devoted to Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on the neural correlations of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but may not be either.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of a non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activities.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) utilizes operative memory.
Seen from this angle, the feelings are closely associated with those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially people.
In connection with the linguistic nature, there is a subtle degradation of perception, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states, so that we can assign them to others next to ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brain stems dedicated to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
