And even if it could be proven in humans, how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even swabs (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case, we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as in a rat, I don’t study language and consciousness, I don’t even examine feelings, I don’t know if they exist.
