Some people think that the street got its name in 1802, when Philip Minthorn’s large farm was divided among several of his children and no one claimed that narrow strip of land.
The back door to Extra Place was led by the CBGB, a punk rock monument that closed in 2006, and the street is perhaps best known as the background photograph on the Ramones album "Rocket to Russia".
“This place was amazing,” says Danny Fields, manager of Ramones, who took the photo in November 1976.
"It was full of rubbish, torn clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, sheets and ropes."
Some locals, including bloggers who write about aggravating the East Village neighborhood, oppose the idea of selling the Extra Place and claim that that piece of public property, though modest, should remain public.
Others consider Extra Place a rarity – an almost unchanged piece of town that should be left as it is.
Jeremiah Moss, who writes a blog called Jeremiah's Missing New York (subtitled "The Book of Crying: A Burning Nostalgic View of the City in the Extinction Process"), raised part of the story of Extra Place from the section Talk about the City, which appeared in The New Yorker newspaper in 1952.
The author of the article, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow, blind alley, dark even in the day and bounded by razor-iron gates of warehouses and stained windows, where a week of old newspapers run through the stoves."
With a few exceptions, the street of one recent evening looked exactly the same.
Krysa passed through the blind end of the street near the door that once led to the CBGB, where today there is an expensive clothing store.
There was graffiti on the walls, and next to a fresh batch of newspapers, there was an empty bottle of beer.
A few passers-by said he rarely thinks of Extra Place, but suggested that he could use some kind of boost.
Fields, on the other hand, said that he thinks that some people underestimate the street’s impact in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he said, "were in places of dark, wet and ugly."
Debate on Bilingualism: Immersion in English
In this edition of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss the position of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a Californian academic and education director at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book “Worse Than You Think: Why Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools.”
Efficiently appealing to Spanish voters is an ominous matter.
Barack Obama’s education agenda only proves that.
Obama’s campaign points out that “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
In order to combat such performance differences, Obama’s education agenda promotes, among other things, “transient bilingual education” for those who are just learning English.
The question remains, however, whether Barack Obama’s commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter primary school in the East Los Angeles district.
The pupils of this school are in the vast majority of cases Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have just recently arrived, are still learning English.
Yet in the state math tests in 2008, an incredible 100 percent of fourth graders got to the highest level.
Nearly ninety-three percent of the astonishing fourth-grade students have reached the highest level in the state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success has been achieved by a method other than the one Obama prefers.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and exercise, continuous assessment of abilities, and unapologetic access.
Furthermore, and this Obama should note, according to Linda Mikels, the director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach to those who are just learning English, is “complete immersion.”
The immersion in English emphasizes the almost noble use of English in the course of teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me, "We had a tremendous success with an entirely new student from Mexico - after twelve months you would go into class and not know who it is."
"It's fun," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take the Sixth Street Prep school as an example of what other schools with large proportions of Spanish and English learners should look like?
The results achieved by the school should make the answer to this question self-evident, but the educational agenda of its own party (the National Education Association is a long-standing supporter of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of dual-language education.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter when he said that people should stop worrying about “only English” laws.
Instead, "you should make sure your children speak Spanish," he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance differences, he should rather think carefully about the educational patterns that work, rather than ridicule them and trivialize them.
Oil is declining sharply due to renewed economic concerns.
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday because of fears that even the U.S. plan to save financial markets would not have to revive the economy.
The prices of futures oil trades fell by 7 percent in the early morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange to $99.80 per barrel.
Since last Monday, prices have fallen by more than $20 per barrel.
Over the past two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by financial turmoil on Wall Street and also by double strong hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After reaching a peak of $145.29 per barrel in July, prices fell to nearly $90 per barrel earlier this month, buzzing back into a wave of huge uncertainty in financial markets.
Investors re-emerged on Monday, even after the congressional presidency announced that it had reached an agreement on the biggest rescue plan in history over the weekend.
This report has been overshadowed by recent concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the latest episode of the ongoing breakdown, the government announced that Citigroup would buy a banking division of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the horrific weekend talks that led to the plan to save the economy "show themselves as unable to revive the mood in the market."
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
