The Pride and Obstacles of Black Lives in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy, and huge, lies a quiet city where the pride and the ardour of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first fully black town to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquettes of turfs, three hundred turrets of turquoise, three hundred turrets of brown leather, three hundred turrets of good."
Now it's a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Festival Zora! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains side-by-side, though it has made it a stop for tourists by including it in a Florida travel guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, worthy and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their real feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what's coming."
Even today, in a year when Black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate on races, many locals remain wary of the views of foreigners.
“We pay great attention to how our story is being told,” says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who lives here from birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of Black rise and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also a shadowed oak by the example of Southern rural Negro culture – sometimes despised, sometimes praised – that originated from American slavery.
It’s not surprising that the locals are both proud and protective.
And concerns about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heart-wrenching books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tour guide have changed the city a little bit to the 17th Street, which leads through the often-passed center of Florida, into the stage of Black history and human drama.
With the defeat of the great drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the shop of the first Eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"Left of the road," she wrote, "is a white-brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned Dash's new widow's husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits the clock hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville was linked to self-government, but also to illiteracy, re-marriage and sex.
This was obviously not the typical publishing house of Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
“Zora said it the way it was,” says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s choir girls who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a cypress emissary, which often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that when she approached the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoked and wore pants in a city that is still proud of decent clothing today.
Most of the population was fascinated, Franklin said, but many fell in love.
"The people have always liked to see Zor," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, had forgotten about her.
Although she was once a literary star, present-day Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood her meaning to the world or her reference at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
Change came in the 80s of the 20th century.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-lane main road.
The dismantling of Orlando has already pushed Interstate Highway No. 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the fifties of the 20th century, the struggle for the mixing of races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"Actually, we had a lady here who killed it.
They threw the melon out of the car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and declared his decision in the Brown v. Chamber of Education to be "offensive to my race rather than ceremonial."
Residents now claim that the disintegration of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesiveness in Eatonville and undermined the courage of local youth.
"Black children were used to hugging - I remember it - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
It lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You don't embrace your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier," said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Zory Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudices with mild self-confidence and quotes such as “How can one resist the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the revival of her reputation.
Five years later, a highly praised Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway came on the shelves in bookstores, which re-introduced it to the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville found the ramp lights again.
Hurston's former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return to the celebration.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
“These five motorway currents have revived, you’d say, directly inflamed, a real civic pride,” Nathiri said.
Boyd said it more simply, "The Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Aliens like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started going to the local church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Registry in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on the repainted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a falling alley in summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Today it is 90 percent black.)
With strangers coming to search for the story and meaning of Eatonville, it is still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required to have in advance, and certain things — such as wall paintings in the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, self-confident teacher who likes to be saturated with red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival grew, so did the domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, crazy, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, comes a sincere love of the village when he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police, which he says would benefit from some help.
And even younger ones, such as 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenonova, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they're just passing by, will think, 'Um, this town is nothing against the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently after the church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we all speak fluently financially.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan were to stay away from newspaper stands and screens on Times Square, they would not have realized that they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never decide that in the swirling bee trap of the offices above their heads, every day, bankers and fund managers who monopolize New York, have had the worst “bad day in the office” since the 1929 crisis.
The envoys keep shoving metal carts down the sidewalks and transfer the muffin bakers to breakfast meetings.
The Hispanics are still moving among the towers and are wearing, like human mules, fifty ragged shirts hanging from wax on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting at the front for their morning bagel at the street food stalls, and it is still not possible to get a yellow taxi on a daily basis between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn’t look like a crisis at all until, with all the talk about pessimism, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I had scheduled this task to cover up with a late-afternoon siege at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about twenty people waiting in the front.
Not in front of the cash registers to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of the bar where older customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for a way to shop with Macy's mixed goods, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker," came for the same reason as me.
But compared to me, they have already chosen their savings from smaller banks in places where they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They chose money from so-called thrifts (slightly similar to construction savings banks), monetary unions and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and who claim to care for their customers as a family.
Over the past year, 15 such banks have quietly collapsed.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a $327 billion bank, went bankrupt, and when New Yorkers returned home on Friday evening, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, tried to catch a rescue buyer.
The employees of the offices and shops that stood in front of me and were afraid of another collapse, moved their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe harbor and that does most of the bailout on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have been learning fluently financially over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, that bank that went bankrupt, and to her obnoxious top executive, Dick Fulda, with such familiarity, as if she were rubbing about a sledgehammer.
And Lyn, the uniformed about fifty-year-old housewife of my agent, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation—Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, "I have my savings in the money market funds now.
I've moved it, I'm not going to risk it."
