"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off-stage." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no collars, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, deviated from the focus on interpretation - only in this way do I achieve the free expression of a man or woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the other hand, a man.
Indistinguishable, if we ignore privacy, in those moments far from the audience - then you can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a fleeting sight or the passionate gesture of hands that are carefree, because they do not intend to go on stage.
German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-people" alternates the theatrical performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this purpose, the photographer composes a unique iconography of flamenco from different environments.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the program Mes de la Fotograf<0xC3><0xAD>a Flamenca, "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco", says the author and explains that "Flamenco-people" "can be any type of people, but when you look at it, you can't look at it.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy... and completely capturing viewers.
To capture the personality of these artists it is not necessary to photograph on stage.
He has his personality and character inside him.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on board cameras.
These are portraits that, thanks to the selection of the camera and the material, resemble a classic photograph.
The use of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical basis of the image and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea which, according to Bauer himself, also mirrors flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, which, however, does not cease to surprise and develop."
What spoils the audience is not the effect of the dance, the song or the play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet the most important, the spirit that appears in the way of perception, being and experiencing, was and is a constant of the work presented during these days in the El Fotomata gallery.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists form famous flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyosov<0xC3><0xA1>, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of flamenco anthology and soon a book edition will be held, which will contain exhibited portraits.
Two years ago, the passion for portraiture led Bauer to the idea of repeating the "Portrait of Sports Veterans" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "photographing people, getting to know them and having the opportunity for a moment, whether longer or just short, to enter their lives - that's my passion.
I think portraits are the most difficult genre in photography.
A person meets or encounters people, personalities that he or she does not even know, or gives him or her only a few minutes to take a photo.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.”
A collection of portraits of the contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Galerie El Fotomata in the street de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hercules, and can be visited until 16 October.
