Conversation – The Blood That Is Again Sure
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its founding and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted because Héma-Québec has become one of the most reliable and effective blood donors in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was contaminated during the 1980s with the immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and the wave of public outbursts, the Canadian government launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster.
While Judge Krever asked to hand over the report, some provinces launched a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, the Gélinea Committee took this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be managed by Québec, and the Canadian Blood Company for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was overwhelming.
With constant efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the next few years, we have regained public confidence," he says and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population had already trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"At that time, we were in Europe witnessing the occurrence of many cases of human form of mad cow disease, new variants of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman, who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, in the case when we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is fatally excreted by the degeneration of the brain, is inevitable.
In April 1999, therefore, we rejected blood from people who had been staying in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect the presence of the virus itself in the donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests were used before.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the period between the moment of infection of the patient and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our technicians, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it and without us being able to figure it out.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one person in every 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, it means that before someone becomes infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
Because Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of transmission of HIV through a blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusions necessary for healing in complete tranquility,” says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of disease-producing element can occur in the system.
Just last year, on the island of Réunion, there was a chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by stinging insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on adequate supply.
“Requirements are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people who offer blood are not accepted on average because, for example, they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited the country where bilge colds occur, they are excluded for one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, to convince people to donate blood is difficult, especially then to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so intact today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” Francine Décary wrote.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, is rich in blood from stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord into the bank and we expect to take them over a thousand a year.
By the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes the program of taking blood from the umbilical cord as very popular.
“Some mothers are disappointed that they don’t have access to it,” because Héma-Québec doesn’t have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
