In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter by Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest producer of gold has launched a lawsuit against three authors and a poor small publishing house for an insult to honor in order to trigger a "transparent public debate" and demands six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for insult to honor, but the law.
It's no surprise that Garver completely misses this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate, to bring down anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the case may be, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend decent sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced fight with an army of lawyers backed by the almost impeccable pockets of the mining company.
The tactics in these unbalanced struggles, by the way, often consist in the destruction of the defendants in order to bring about a conciliation procedure that will shut the mouth of the opposite party and, moreover, terrifies anyone who dares to engage in this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it had to present its view of the whole thing to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate is in the normal circumstances in exchange of thoughts, not in the early obscurity.
The mining companies, therefore, were not enough to open their books, their documentation, and to create a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole thing.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and mocks petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a “public debate” while at the same time dismissing the views of the same public?
It seems that this word in the Vice President’s world refers only to fat-paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; that’s a pretty narrow notion of the term.
In a democracy, they also have the right to speak out.
Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – that the public that supports Noir Canada’s authors and publishers does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining companies.
The public is prepared to listen to Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a lawsuit, in which they are to be shut up to the defendant's mouth (in the context of their lawsuit, to have a term for a "public debate" Barri's company).
Forgetting the surreal Garver speech, the pursuit initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to seek and seek the truth that is essential for every democratic society.
