Wall Street Rescue Operations – Democrats and Republicans Understand Each Other
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to curb the financial crisis that has been plagued by Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of deposited public money, new measures to capture the number of homes occupied due to non-payment of workers, and also the right to monitor the amount of salaries paid by employers.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, after the two-day negotiation marathon ended.
“We have made great progress and we have reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the current crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
"That's the key point: if we don't do it, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption of everyday life of Americans will be huge," Republican Judd Gregg said.
In the last few hours, the negotiations have been running at maximum turnovers out of fear of the effect, which would be another failure on the mood of investors.
The set time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the U.S. president were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed rather in favour of the agreement, but did not neglect to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has endorsed the addition of an agreement on some measures, in particular the one aimed at allowing owners to keep their homes, and the wage measures for leading labor-saved companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there’s nothing to congratulate.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the television waves.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I would like to see details, but I hope so."
“The rough features I’ve read [shows] that it’s something that we’re all going to have to spend and with which it’s going to be possible to move forward.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the 700 billion plan is to buy dubious receivables and risk and non-sale assets of U.S. financial institutions for taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after a 14-month crisis sparked by a bubble in the real estate market, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to another, more widespread form of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and in the breakdown of financial institutions.
The failure of last week’s first draft of the agreement has been brought to the attention of Republican members.
Since the Democrats have agreed that some of the “toxic” assets of troubled companies will only be guaranteed by the government, but will not buy them back, there is a belief that the non-Eastern situation is ignited.
In an effort to approximate conflicting views in Congress, a measure was attached that stipulated that the government would be able to introduce new charges that would help it recover its deposit if it had to take over losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan counts on a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion is expected to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will gain shares in the saved companies, which in the event of profits will pay him dividends and which he will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of property related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to employees of affected companies.
The drafters of the plan would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it is not yet clear whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, the vote against this project continued to rise in both the Republican and the Democratic camps.
"It is clear that Washington will not hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, said in a statement.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But earning money from taxpayers is not a solution.”
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen called the "sceptics committee", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred esteemed professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: We ask Congress not to be in a hurry and carefully examine which way to go," he said.
At the same time, Europe reaffirmed that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the brink of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) to the states as a result of the crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is among the 20 largest European banks and among the ten largest insurers.
"We are not going to lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
“In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that is precisely what the organizers and households can appreciate in today’s uncertain times.”
On the other side of the Channel, it seems, the British government has started to nationalize other banks affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing Bradford and Bringley loans, of which more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans for the purchase of real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will purchase branches and client accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the UK government since the financial crisis began.
