The psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been able to reveal to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to be late in an eBay auction competition, so they would rather pay too high a price.
Research using an experimental auction attempted to map out the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a play auction, and the active areas of the brain of subjects were studied using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method.
In both games, the participants could win money, but while playing at the auction, the important element of which is to overcome the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex called the striatum began to work intensely when losing.
This area of the brain plays, among many other functions, a role in the "self-replacement" mechanism of the nervous system.
Screwing up the price is therefore, according to the researchers, possible to explain the effort to avoid the sharp reaction of the striate.
To support their theory, members of the research team from the ranks of economists conducted a cross-sectional financial survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product in question, and they made bets.
Members of the other group were also promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive another $15 in reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost that money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, was that everything was in the fact that one was emphasized the win and the other the loss.
However, members of the group playing "against the loss" were willing to go higher than in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
“These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the phenomena that can be observed in the auctions of the joys of winning and avoiding the risk.
Until neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, we have now reached a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York's Faculty of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
The number of home cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are being treated. The reason for this is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary of the names of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the causes of the disease and the disease caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways depending on the origins of the disease: hepatitis type A and E digestive systems (for example, infected with food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other viruses of blood and body fluids (sperm, semen, semen).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against viruses A and B, there is no type C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, compulsion to vomit.
Then, yellowing, light stools and dark urine are formed on the skin and eyelids. The treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from the most serious form of this disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected do not even know that the cause of the disease destroys liver cells invasively, so in many cases the first symptoms will arrive in 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent timely, to carry out regular de-pistolation.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already prove a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his/her medical practitioner if he/she notices any signs of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
