Intelligent car mimics the year of a beetle
What would be the best way to develop technologies capable of preventing collisions if not for the imitation of obstacles detectors in the natural world?
For example, bees.
The basic strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the CEATEC in Japan, was injected by engineers from Nissan. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a biomimetic BR23C-type robotic control system, a robotic mini-car equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all crashes.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging,” Kazuhiro Doi, the brand’s chief technology officer for PR and R&D, explained at the exhibition.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see in all directions at an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eye, the engineers came up with the idea of a laser telescope.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in the 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into a collision prevention operation.
The obstacle is caught during a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to mimic the bee movements and by rotating the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this outgoing maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, a robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective packaging, inside which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or angularly, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoided, only the possibility of rotational motion, acceleration and slowdown was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent response is important, not the ability to process, let alone the storage of data.
This mechanism has to process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store them and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so only a few kilobytes of memory is constantly used.
It does not need memory with gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates could get into mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another option of application may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the driver to the specified final destination.
