As in the U.S., so in Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator of phenomena that have been in incubation for a long time, which are shrinking in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactivation, the extraordinary revival of the market, the double category of State-power in relation to a certain renationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but which mainly involve the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This has created a political problem for those who run it: it means how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be significantly out of the question or has nothing to add: the obvious evidence has been given by the European Union, which is as always divided between different interests and different national strategies and which cannot decide on a single common political line.
And so everyone waits for the intervention of the government of each individual state, the rescue plans, the revival of the market, the new rules and, above all, the distribution of funds: the moment we get to the emergency, only the states have the economic resources, the amount of financial resources to be able to afford themselves.
It also possesses the necessary resources and authorizations to use them: two sources of immense value, under certain circumstances which, perhaps, no market and no international organization will ever be able to have to the same extent.
This new emphasis, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, by the way, in full compliance with the growing importance which is trying to attribute the latest economic advances to one factor closely linked to it: territorial citizenship.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of sitta, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finances were as predestined as ever to dominate the world by the powers of the world, we would have realized from nothing that the world was so predestined to dominate them.
